# Runbook: PR patrol

PR patrol watches for open PRs with unresolved review threads and auto-files
a follow-up issue (plus an idle worker shell) so they don't go stale.

## First boot sweeps the whole backlog

When PR-patrol coverage is newly enabled for a workspace, its first pass
walks every currently-open PR with unresolved threads — expect a burst of
follow-up issues and idle shells the first time, not a slow trickle.

## Scope it to specific authors

`pr_patrol.author_logins` limits patrol to listed authors' PRs; leaving it
unset patrols everyone's. Set it with `mcp__arbiter__workspace_config_set`
(CLI: `arb config set`) — never a raw API PATCH — see the Config Safety
pitfall in the field guide.

## Config changes take effect on the next patrol cycle, not instantly

PR patrol re-reads its workspace config fresh on every tick (default
interval: 60s) — a config change (like adjusting `author_logins`) does
*not* need a restart, but can lag up to one tick behind. If a scope change
doesn't seem to have applied, wait for the next cycle before assuming
something's broken.
